  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Indigenous communities working towards human devlpmnt and resilience in the context of climate change</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Bolivia and Guatemala are two countries with large indigenous populations, many of whom are small-scale rural farmers living in poverty, frequently impacted by the negative effects of climate change and environmental degradation. In recent years, there has been an increase in the unpredictability of rainfall and climate change that has exacerbated climatic phenomena such as frosts, hailstorms and droughts which have affected crops and production. Both countries have seen an increase in the adoption of modern farming practices which use registered seeds and chemical farming products. These practices are unsustainable for families in poverty, are causing significant damage to the environment and are threatening the protection of local indigenous heritage. The negative effects of climate change and environmental degradation, as well as extractive development models and large-scale farming (mono-crops), are currently threatening agricultural rural families&#x2019; and indigenous communities&#x2019; livelihoods and are reducing their income generation, particularly for those communities and families that depend on small plots of land. Rural farmers and indigenous communities, particularly women, in both regions are often affected by low self-esteem and sometimes undervalue the importance of their traditional knowledge, particularly their techniques to adapt crops to climate change. In the face of low levels of support by the State, structural inequality and closing civil society spaces, communities need support more than ever in building their networks and increasing their knowledge, confidence and decision-making capacity. CAFOD partners CENDA (Bolivia) and PSCV (Guatemala &#x2013; GUA181) will carry out a three-year project with support from CAFOD and JOA (Government of Jersey) to support poor rural indigenous communities in responding to these challenges, sharing together their knowledge and experiences. This project covers the Bolivian component of the joint venture.</narrative>
  </description>
